Halong Violet Junk, amazing......
Spent only 2 days and one night on the junk unfortunately, the bay itself, amazing. Better times of the year to see it as visibility wasn't great and it rained occasionally, but it does not ruin it at all. Halong Violet, the junk we went on was amazing. Maximum of 12 guests (6 very large rooms) but 20 staff, so service is great. Food was spectacular. Anyone looking to do an overnight junk tour, should look this one up. Either way, Halong Bay, a must do, and should be on everyone's list to see.
Written March 20, 2012
BGillman-202
Dublin, Ireland54 contributions
Paloma cruise major disappointment
Jan 2012 ‚Ä¢ Couples
We spent 2 days and one night on the Paloma cruise and overall were very disappointed in both the cruise and the level of service offered which we considered fell well below the standard we expected.
On the plus side the boat is in excellent condition with modern cabins. The beds are hard with good quality pillows, and have a good shower with plenty of hot water.
The negatives, and there are many, fall into 2 broad categories, itinerary and customer service.
In relation to the itinerary, we had two issues, firstly this isn't much of a cruise. The boat travels out from a reasonably busy port to its overnight anchor within about 1.5 hours. During this time you don't see much of Hao Long bay. The boat does not move from this spot except when it goes straight back to port the next day. That is the case whether you are doing the 1 night or 2 night version. Of the supposed 2,000 pillars in the bay I think we saw 40 at a guess. My big issue with the itinerary however was the total failure to plan for the weather, or to customise the tour to the season.
On the first day there were to be 3 activities, visit a beach or canoeing, sunset viewing and squid fishing. 2 of these were done by no one. Our guide cheerfully told us that in January they only see the sunset about 4 times a month and that there were no squid in the bay at this time of year. I don't understand why they hadn't bothered to tailor the itinerary to reflect these common issues and organised something else.
We did visit a beach with a hike to view the bay and some people did the canoeing. It was ok, but I should point out that it was seriously cold. It felt about 8 degrees, as I kept checking if I could see my breath. So I wouldn't do that again. We also noticed that the 3 day people got the privilege of a beach barbecue as part of the extra day. I'm delighted we didn't put ourselves through that in the cold.
To my second issue, the customer service. Our guide was borderline rude and really only appeared to care about incurring minimal hassle. There was nowhere to sit and relax on the boat as there were no heaters or rain covers on deck. The boat has an indoor bar with some couches but the staff always sat there talking and guests didn't appear welcome, so no one sat there. Instead guests either sat on the bed in their cabins or at the formal dinner tables if they wanted to read or relax.
To crown it all the food was also poor, for example on the last day lunch was served in the harbour almost within view of the Paloma shore office. It consisted of cold chips, boiled broccoli and 3 roasted shrimp. No sauce, no flavours nothing. It was the most miserable looking dish. Actually, on the whole the food was nearly always cold.
So in summary, I would not do this cruise in January, and even in fine weather I would do it as a day trip and sleep onshore. That should save enough to contribute towards a real cruise (I.e one where you actually cruise somewhere).
Written January 14, 2012
Sharen
Brighton, UK272 contributions
Halong Bay cruise - 2nights on Paloma
Nov 2011 ‚Ä¢ Couples
Our hotel (Golden Sun in Hanoi) recommended this junk as our selected junk was fully booked. We were very happy with the Paloma. We took a standard room and they were very comfortable, as was the bed. The bathroom was on the small side and the shower didn't have a lot of water pressure but what do you expect?! The water was heated and they provided all the shampoo, soaps & even toothbrush and comb! The food was generally very good. More importantly, there was plenty of deck space for everyone to eat outside on a balcony, lounge around on a sun bed, or snuggle up on the coaches near the captains cabin.
I strongly recomend the 2 night tour. It is a full 3 to 4 hour bus trip up to Halong and the extra day does give you some time to relax and unwind and fully appreciate this beautiful location.
The Paloma definitely looked like one of the best boats that we saw and you couldn't want anything more from the boat. We did have a difficult guest on our cruise and our guide handled him quite well too.
The only thing I will point out is that some guests were doing a 1 night cruise, and some 2 nights. This means that the Paloma does not travel further from the port on the 2 night cruise; it remains near the port so the 1 night guests can be taken back. I had assumed that travelling for 2 nights meant we would travel further around Halong Bay but this is not the case.
